snippet.textDisplay: I saw the Force Awakens a couple times and never really felt that it jumped out of the screen at me, the story was not original, the visuals were eh and Rey was just a big Mary Sue. The Last Jedi made sequences from other films make no sense. Johnson took many liberties with the physics of Jedi and Spacecrafts. He introduced themes in the 8th movie of a franchise about the Skywalkers that were completely irrelevant. And it was an hour longer than it needed to be. It was the first time in a movie theater that I've almost fallen asleep. When I rewatched the movie on Netflix I saw the flaws in everything even clearer, example: throne room fight choreography. The only bad parts of Rise for me were the repetitive fan service, the constant jokes from C-3PO and the things Abrams kept in the background from TLJ. Abrams almost went overboard with the spectacle of this movie but still produced cohesive action scenes. Palpatine seemed rushed but it made sense by the power of his character and from the stance of the filmmaker. Kylo Ren had an incredible arch that concluded so well in this movie. The force energy and life force elements were so well done. It's one of my favorite star Wars movies already.

The prequels work and this new trilogy doesn’t because.... lemme put it this way: As a Christian, when a pastor presents a sermon on Jesus, there’s resonance; it reaches the heart of the story. BUT..... then try to watch the History Channel talk about Jesus... sure they might have some good visuals and maybe even Morgan Freeman is narrating... but there’s no heart, no doctrine, no faith, no love, and even the so-called facts aren’t quite hitting the mark.

Well, George Lucas is Star Wars’ pastor. He might not have delivered his best sermon, but at least he understood what he was talking about. Disney is the History Channel. They don’t understand the rules, the lore, and they have no respect in their heart for the source material.

It’s an empty shell that appeases audiences that just wanna be entertained, but it’s absolute blasphemy to die-hard fans!

snippet.textDisplay:
The thing that SW fans need to admit to themselves - and they never will because nothing's ever their fault, in their eyes - is that the blood pouring from the wounds of the Sequel Trilogy as a result of this movie is on their hands, too. It's undeniable. The fanbase has been pulling the strings on this franchise since it's been under Disney's control. They'll never accept or believe that because they've claimed they haven't gotten what they wanted, but in point of fact, they actually did...it just wasn't given to them the way they wanted it. To wit:

Fans complained about TFA being too similar to A New Hope; it's one of the biggest points of contention for that film. So, when Rian Johnson took over for The Last Jedi, he took the playbook that Abrams started with and tossed it away like Luke tossed away his lightsaber. "Luke's going to be a hermit, riddled with guilt over his failure to protect Ben from darkness. Rey is a nobody, born from parents who were nobodies. Snoke is not as important to this story as Palpatine was to the OT and PT, cuz Ben's gonna kill him and we don't find out who Snoke was and why he was so important." Fans HATED that, complaining that Johnson character-assassinated Luke, made Rey into a Mary Sue that doesn't make any sense and turned Snoke into a completely irrelevant character.

So, once Trevorrow was out of the picture whatever mess he was going to make - and trust me; if you saw Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom, there was no way his version of Ep 9 wasn't going to be terrible - and Kathleen Kennedy got Abrams to come back, he's painted into a creative corner. "Well, shit! I did this thing and fans complained; Johnson changed everything and the fans hated that even more. Now what do we do?"

So, we got a film made up of several admittedly cool-looking sequences stitched together with the barest minimum of a plot and sloppily constructed answers to the biggest nitpicks ("Rey's a Palpatine; that's why she's so powerful!", "Snoke was created by Palpatine; that's why he didn't matter as much!", "Luke backtracks on his behavior at he beginning of TLJ") and packed with "memberberries" including Palpatine, Lando, a Luke Force-ghost appearance, the Yavin medal (and Chewie finally getting one), Sith mythology, old-style Star Destroyers with Death-Star-like superlasers, and the voices of Anakin, Obi-Wan, Ahsoka, Qui-Gon, Yoda, Mace Windu, etc. Abrams and Terrio pandered to the nostalgia-obsessed portion of the fanbase - the ones who thought the only good thing about Rogue One was the Darth Vader scene - and said, "There, do you love us now?"

Oops...guess not, cuz now the fanbase is more polluted and toxic than ever with even more whiny, spittle-flecked rage...and the best thing about it? It's partly their fault.

So, we got a film made up of several admittedly cool-looking sequences stitched together with the barest minimum of a plot and sloppily constructed answers to the biggest nitpicks ("Rey's a Palpatine; that's why she's so powerful!", "Snoke was created by Palpatine; that's why he didn't matter as much!", "Luke backtracks on his behavior at he beginning of TLJ") and packed with "memberberries" including Palpatine, Lando, a Luke Force-ghost appearance, the Yavin medal (and Chewie finally getting one), Sith mythology, old-style Star Destroyers with Death-Star-like superlasers, and the voices of Anakin, Obi-Wan, Ahsoka, Qui-Gon, Yoda, Mace Windu, etc.  Abrams and Terrio pandered to the nostalgia-obsessed portion of the fanbase - the ones who thought the only good thing about Rogue One was the Darth Vader scene -  and said, "There, do you love us now?"

Oops...guess not, cuz now the fanbase is more polluted and toxic than ever with even more whiny, spittle-flecked rage...and the best thing about it?  It's partly their fault.
